1. What is Pattern Designs and explain its significance?\par
a. Design Patterns are efficient solutions to the General Software Design problems.\par
b. The common problems are resolved by applying these Design Patterns which are\par
the best practices to obtain efficient solutions for the complex known and\par
common problems in the design challenges of the software design and\par
development processes.\par
c. These design solutions for the common problems were obtained after performing\par
several trial and error methods by many developers for a long time in many\par
designs to obtain these effective solutions to the commonly known problems.\par
d. There are different types of Design patterns. They are Behavioral Patterns,\par
Creational Patterns, and Structural Patterns.\par
\par
2. What are the different uses of Design Patterns?\par
a. Speeds up the development process\par
b. Ensures effective and efficient software designs\par
c. More reusability for the common problems across the design model\par
d. Enables code readability\par
e. Good documentation and easier to maintain for other developers\par
f. Robust applications can be developed\par
g. Ensures customer retention for delivering efficient and robust solutions\par
\par
3. What are the different types of Design Patterns and explain?\par
a. Behavioral Pattern: The Behavioral Pattern is all about the communication\par
between the several objects of the classes. It mainly concentrates on the\par
communication and invocation between the objects.\par
b. Creational Pattern: The Creational Pattern is about the instantiation of the class\par
and also further extends to the object creation. This category can be further\par
divided into Class creational patterns and object creational patterns. The main\par
theme used in this pattern is a delegation to get the work done. It mainly\par
depends on the delegation model.\par
c. Structural Pattern: The composition of the classes\par
and objects while interacting with several other classes. This ensures the\par
application is more loosely coupled than getting complex.\par
\par
4. What is Singleton Pattern and how can it be implemented in C#?\par
a. Its a design pattern that comes under the Creational design\par
pattern which is used to instantiate only a single object from that class. Finally,\par
that class will be confined only to a single object in its entire life cycle.\par
b. The Singleton design pattern is very important in hiding the class instantiation\par
functionality to be hidden from the other classes in order to maintain the object\par
instantiation limitations for the purpose of application or design requirements to\par
be fulfilled. Always only a single instance can be created from the Singleton\par
Design pattern.\par
c. In C# this can be implemented using the single constructor which is given with\par
access keyword private and without any parameters i.e., default no-args\par
constructor.\par
d. This method does not provide any thread safety.\par
\par
5. What is meant by Managed and Unmanaged code?\par
a. The code that is managed by the CLR is called Managed code. This code runs\par
inside the CLR. Hence, it is necessary to install the .Net framework in order to\par
execute the managed code. CLR manages memory through garbage collection\par
and also uses the other features like CAS and CTS for efficient management of\par
the code.\par
b. Unmanaged code is any code that does not depend on CLR for execution. It\par
means it is developed by any other language independent of .Net framework. It\par
uses its own runtime environment for compiling and execution.\par
c. Though it is not running inside the CLR, the unmanaged code will work properly\par
if all the other parameters are correctly followed.\par
